  "text": "Male Sprague-Dawley rats (125 to 150 g; Charles River Laboratories, Wilmington, Mass) were adrenalectomized, then given 0.9% saline to drink and fed 23% protein chow ad libitum as described previously. [CITATION_1] After 14 days, osmotic minipumps (Model 2001, Alzet) containing 8.3 mg/mL aldosterone (Research Plus Inc) in 10% dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) in saline or vehicle alone were implanted subcutaneously in the midscapular region. The infusion rate was 8.3 g/d (approximately 1.3 mg/kg per day). Rats were sacrificed after 7 days, and blood and aortas were collected. Serum aldosterone levels were determined by radioimmunoassay (Diagnostics Products Corp).",
